WEBVTT

00:02.127 --> 00:04.420
NARRATOR: Previously on
Terminator: The Sarah Connor Chronicles:

00:04.587 --> 00:06.588
SARAH:
I'm thinking I love you.

00:06.756 --> 00:07.798
Always remember that.

00:08.049 --> 00:09.925
You wanna stop Skynet? This is the way.

00:11.428 --> 00:13.929
CHARLIE: Eight years.
-I didn't wanna leave you.

00:15.515 --> 00:16.765
I didn't have a choice.

00:16.933 --> 00:19.768
-You're married?
-Yeah, I am.

00:20.061 --> 00:22.438
When we jumped through time,
I died of cancer.

00:22.605 --> 00:24.106
Yes, 2005.

00:24.274 --> 00:26.358
-Am I still gonna get sick?
-I don't know.

00:26.609 --> 00:27.943
-Aah!
-She's bleeding out.

00:30.780 --> 00:32.448
SARAH:
There's a warehouse in the desert.

00:36.119 --> 00:38.454
Everybody who knew
about the factory is dead.

00:38.621 --> 00:39.705
Well, I'm not.

00:39.873 --> 00:41.331
Kaliba was building something.

00:41.499 --> 00:42.875
Hey, baby.

00:43.835 --> 00:45.669
You were pregnant. Now you aren't.

00:45.879 --> 00:47.504
-You care about this girl?
JOHN: Yeah.

00:47.672 --> 00:49.673
She's a security risk.

00:54.804 --> 00:56.722
-What are you doing?
-Moving.

00:56.973 --> 00:59.391
Yeah, well, seems about the right time
for that.

01:13.948 --> 01:15.157
SARAH:
When John was a child...

01:15.325 --> 01:18.327
...the legends of the jungle
were his fairy tales.

01:18.536 --> 01:19.703
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

01:19.871 --> 01:23.332
His favorite was
the story of El Viejo del Monte.

01:25.043 --> 01:27.669
The Old Man of the Forest.

01:28.213 --> 01:31.673
A merciless hunter
who killed every animal in his path.

01:31.841 --> 01:35.844
El Viejo didn't eat his prey.
He left it behind to rot in the soil.

01:36.012 --> 01:39.515
To teach him a lesson,
the gods turned him into a simisco...

01:39.682 --> 01:40.974
...half animal, half man.

01:41.142 --> 01:43.268
[BIRD SCREECHING]

01:43.478 --> 01:45.479
[WINGS FLAPPING]

01:46.731 --> 01:50.526
He was condemned
to defend the jungle for all eternity.

01:51.402 --> 01:53.695
JOHN:
Mom. Mom.

01:55.865 --> 01:57.866
This was El Viejo's punishment.

01:58.034 --> 02:00.202
This was his curse.

02:00.370 --> 02:02.204
To forever be vigilant.

02:02.372 --> 02:04.873
To forever protect.

02:11.381 --> 02:12.589
Look.

02:15.635 --> 02:18.679
[CHIRPING]

02:19.430 --> 02:20.722
We have to keep moving.

02:22.392 --> 02:23.767
Why are we so far from camp?

02:23.935 --> 02:26.228
I told you, it's part of the game.

02:26.396 --> 02:27.479
You mean training.

02:28.064 --> 02:30.732
Well, if we call it a game, it's more fun.

02:30.900 --> 02:32.192
But it's not a game.

02:32.360 --> 02:34.236
The point...

02:35.238 --> 02:36.238
...is listen to me.

02:36.406 --> 02:38.574
I always listen. You don't talk that much.

02:42.745 --> 02:44.705
JOHN:
We gotta go.

03:03.183 --> 03:05.934
How long will it take you
to pack up the storage locker?

03:06.728 --> 03:10.355
A while. There's some explosives
that need securing.

03:10.523 --> 03:12.858
Make sure you get to the safe house
before night.

03:13.026 --> 03:14.276
It can be hard to find.

03:14.444 --> 03:17.779
-I can follow directions.
-Well, you can also make mistakes.

03:20.033 --> 03:22.326
Wouldn't want anyone else hurt
because of them.

03:22.493 --> 03:25.120
CAMERON:
Thirty-three-42-31 north.

03:25.288 --> 03:29.291
The safe house coordinates.
It's in the desert.

03:29.500 --> 03:31.376
You like the desert.

03:32.545 --> 03:33.754
Things happen out there.

03:33.963 --> 03:35.505
Things happen here too.

03:38.134 --> 03:40.302
We're starting over.

03:41.137 --> 03:44.765
Whatever happened here
is no one's fault.

03:47.477 --> 03:49.311
Let's get out of here.

03:53.983 --> 03:59.863
[ENGINE STARTS]

04:25.515 --> 04:28.684
-Hello, Savannah. How are you today?
-I'm well.

04:28.851 --> 04:31.019
Would you like to play a game?

04:31.187 --> 04:33.605
Engaging in imaginative play
helps my development.

04:35.733 --> 04:40.529
This is Mount Valmai,
hiding place of the Mask of Life.

04:40.697 --> 04:43.073
The Toa protect the mask
from the Dark Hunters.

04:45.326 --> 04:52.207
These are the ducklings.
Chickie, Fluffy and Feathers.

04:52.375 --> 04:53.542
Can they play too?

04:53.710 --> 04:57.462
I don't think there are any ducklings
on the mystical island of Voya Nui.

04:57.714 --> 04:59.881
Are you sure?

05:00.049 --> 05:03.719
I'm sorry. I've accessed all the files.
I can find no references to them...

05:03.886 --> 05:05.887
...in any of the instructions.

05:07.098 --> 05:08.223
What's wrong?

05:08.391 --> 05:11.393
Would you like one of the Toa instead?

05:12.061 --> 05:13.270
No.

05:13.438 --> 05:16.440
The ducklings are sad
because they can't play.

05:16.607 --> 05:19.401
Can't you change the rules
to make them happy?

05:22.238 --> 05:23.363
Yes.

05:24.198 --> 05:25.866
We can change the rules.

05:35.877 --> 05:37.878
[MACHINES POWERING DOWN]

06:12.288 --> 06:18.668
[IN ROBOTIC VOICE] What is all this about?
-John Henry, stop! Let go, please!

06:20.213 --> 06:24.132
John Henry, please. You're hurting me.

06:24.842 --> 06:32.307
-Ow! John Henry, stop! Let go! Please! Stop!
-I understand what this is about.

06:32.850 --> 06:34.017
[SCREAMS]

06:44.070 --> 06:47.531
[MACHINE POWERING DOWN]

06:48.366 --> 06:49.616
[GASPS]

07:05.508 --> 07:07.509
[STATIC OVER RADIO]

07:09.637 --> 07:12.139
Static. It's weird.

07:12.849 --> 07:15.350
There's some interference or something.

07:22.150 --> 07:24.734
-What the hell?
-Bug slug.

07:25.403 --> 07:26.653
Bug slug? Are you serious?

07:26.821 --> 07:28.613
We just passed it.

07:30.783 --> 07:33.118
We haven't played Bug Slug
since I was like 8.

07:33.286 --> 07:35.370
You can't start playing
without telling me.

07:35.538 --> 07:37.497
Fine. We're playing Bug Slug.

07:39.000 --> 07:41.751
-What if I don't wanna play?
-Too late. Already started.

07:43.796 --> 07:46.465
-Are you feeling all right?
-I feel great.

07:46.632 --> 07:49.050
You feel great? Why?

07:49.260 --> 07:52.596
We haven't been on the road together
for a long time, that's all.

07:52.889 --> 07:54.264
What's so great about it?

07:58.311 --> 08:01.480
Don't teach Bug Slug to Cameron.
She could do some real damage.

08:02.231 --> 08:03.273
[CHUCKLES]

08:04.025 --> 08:06.151
God, this signal really blows.

08:09.572 --> 08:11.239
Hey, desert's that way.

08:11.407 --> 08:13.241
We're taking a detour.

08:18.372 --> 08:20.749
So I've got good news,
I've got bad news...

08:20.917 --> 08:23.335
...and I have really bad news.

08:24.212 --> 08:27.130
The good news is what we've got
isn't an engineering problem.

08:27.298 --> 08:29.174
All of John Henry's processes look okay.

08:29.342 --> 08:33.136
-Daemons are running fine--
-Wait a minute, his demons?

08:33.513 --> 08:37.432
Oh, yeah, his Daemons. D-A-E-M-O-N.

08:37.600 --> 08:40.185
It's a term for a program
that runs in the background.

08:40.353 --> 08:42.270
All computers like John Henry have them.

08:42.438 --> 08:44.814
Daemons run the lights,
manage the elevators...

08:44.982 --> 08:48.693
...the security systems.
All kinds of daemons. Everywhere.

08:48.861 --> 08:50.195
Okay.

08:52.156 --> 08:55.242
So, what caused John Henry's
daemons to go crazy?

08:55.409 --> 08:57.244
MURCH:
That's the bad news.

08:58.329 --> 08:59.621
It came from the outside.

09:00.831 --> 09:02.082
A cyber-attack?

09:02.250 --> 09:05.252
Which brings me to the really bad news.

09:05.419 --> 09:08.046
And by "bad news" I mean,
on a scale of one to 10...

09:08.214 --> 09:11.675
...one being a hangnail,
10 being Katrina...

09:12.260 --> 09:14.135
...this is Katrina with a hangnail.

09:16.180 --> 09:18.723
Someone managed to stuff
malware down the throat...

09:18.891 --> 09:21.351
...of the most sophisticated AI
in human history.

09:23.104 --> 09:26.273
John Henry was infiltrated. Probed.

09:27.400 --> 09:29.442
Well, looks worse than that to me.

09:29.610 --> 09:32.112
Looks like someone out there
wants to kill him.

09:38.953 --> 09:40.370
You been into my plastique?

09:40.538 --> 09:41.621
I needed it.

09:41.831 --> 09:44.416
You know what?
I can handle the rest myself.

09:44.584 --> 09:46.167
Sarah sent both of us here.

09:46.335 --> 09:48.878
Yeah. To get John away from you.

09:49.046 --> 09:50.338
Or from you.

09:56.137 --> 09:57.971
Don't touch this.

09:58.139 --> 09:59.764
We're supposed to get everything.

09:59.932 --> 10:01.766
I've got this.

10:04.145 --> 10:06.271
That jacket belongs to Jesse.

10:06.439 --> 10:08.565
Don't talk about her.

10:08.858 --> 10:10.817
Okay? You don't know
anything about her.

10:13.195 --> 10:14.404
I know that you loved her.

10:16.532 --> 10:19.659
You wouldn't have fathered a child
with her if you didn't.

10:21.996 --> 10:24.247
I'm sorry for your loss.

10:26.208 --> 10:28.001
What?

10:29.545 --> 10:31.921
-I'm sorry for your loss.
-What loss?

10:32.465 --> 10:34.674
The child you fathered with Jesse.

10:35.551 --> 10:39.304
The one she was carrying
aboard the SS Jimmy Carter.

10:39.764 --> 10:40.972
The one that died.

10:42.975 --> 10:44.267
[PANTING]

10:49.148 --> 10:51.191
I never had a kid.

10:52.652 --> 10:54.903
-You can't kill me.
-I can try.

10:57.865 --> 10:59.783
Tell me what you're talking about.

11:00.993 --> 11:03.161
She was pregnant.

11:03.996 --> 11:05.080
She miscarried.

11:26.894 --> 11:29.312
Why did you tell me that now?

11:32.274 --> 11:35.360
You put John in danger
when you lied about Jesse.

11:37.071 --> 11:39.948
Sarah nearly lost her child.

11:40.658 --> 11:42.659
You lost a child.

11:42.827 --> 11:44.661
You won't make that mistake again.

11:46.956 --> 11:48.123
You knew her.

11:49.250 --> 11:50.583
I met her once.

11:52.211 --> 11:53.628
She never told me that.

11:54.672 --> 11:57.632
It seems she never told you
a lot of things.

12:17.737 --> 12:19.821
What is this place?

12:45.139 --> 12:47.849
Hey. Hey, come here.

12:48.058 --> 12:50.226
What are you doing here, huh?

12:50.394 --> 12:51.478
Who lives here?

12:55.733 --> 12:56.941
Come here.

13:16.128 --> 13:17.170
Charlie.

13:19.048 --> 13:23.259
Hey, Johnny. Hey.

13:39.777 --> 13:43.822
-You like bouillabaisse?
-I may. I don't know. What is it?

13:44.031 --> 13:46.115
It's French for fish soup.

13:48.577 --> 13:49.953
Mm.

13:50.412 --> 13:53.540
-That's very good. Very good.
-The secret's the fresh tomatoes.

13:54.542 --> 13:55.708
I grow them myself.

13:55.918 --> 13:57.335
You grow tomatoes?

13:58.003 --> 13:59.546
Yeah. Think that's funny?

13:59.755 --> 14:01.047
Don't you?

14:01.882 --> 14:03.633
I got a lot of time on my hands.

14:03.801 --> 14:06.427
You know?
Might as well put it to good use.

14:07.304 --> 14:08.429
[DOOR OPENS]

14:15.229 --> 14:16.813
She's been here before.

14:17.398 --> 14:19.232
Not with me.

14:19.650 --> 14:22.569
She set this house up after Michelle died.

14:23.237 --> 14:24.362
Hey, want more soup?

14:25.364 --> 14:26.823
-Sure.
-Yeah.

14:30.536 --> 14:32.245
All right.

14:33.122 --> 14:35.498
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

14:37.376 --> 14:40.670
-Did she tell you why we're here?
-No, she didn't.

14:42.381 --> 14:44.507
Spare room's in there.

14:46.677 --> 14:48.761
JOHN:
We're spending the night?

14:51.140 --> 14:54.893
-What about Derek and Cameron?
-We'll meet up with them tomorrow.

14:57.438 --> 15:00.440
Hey, I could use a hand on the boat.

15:00.608 --> 15:01.983
Got some work to do.

15:02.151 --> 15:04.736
Yeah, let me get my gear.

15:07.740 --> 15:09.407
[DOOR OPENS]

15:11.076 --> 15:12.243
Smells good.

15:21.003 --> 15:23.046
There's bread in the fridge.

15:23.505 --> 15:25.340
Some peanut butter.

15:25.674 --> 15:27.425
Help yourself.

15:28.469 --> 15:30.219
SARAH:
Charlie.

15:34.350 --> 15:35.892
I won't be here long.

15:36.477 --> 15:38.227
No. No, you won't.

15:41.190 --> 15:42.941
[METALLIC CLINKING]

15:44.360 --> 15:47.695
So she was from the future
and you knew? The whole time?

15:49.740 --> 15:51.866
Not the whole time.

15:52.576 --> 15:55.203
I suspected something...

15:55.371 --> 15:57.538
...but it just took a while to figure it out.

16:01.335 --> 16:02.961
Did you love her?

16:04.713 --> 16:07.674
She was a good person. I don't know.

16:10.886 --> 16:12.762
Maybe if things were different.

16:12.930 --> 16:15.431
CHARLIE:
Yeah, well, I guess you could say that...

16:17.017 --> 16:18.893
...about a lot of things.

16:19.061 --> 16:21.437
Could say that about
my whole life, but it's not...

16:21.605 --> 16:23.564
...so, what's the point?

16:41.959 --> 16:43.793
The first week...

16:45.045 --> 16:46.921
...I kept seeing her.

16:48.757 --> 16:52.301
I'd go to the market, she'd be there.

16:52.845 --> 16:55.263
For a second, my heart would stop.

16:56.348 --> 17:00.685
Then I'd realize,
"Hey, that's not my wife."

17:01.478 --> 17:05.231
That's some random woman who wears
her hair the way Michelle used to.

17:06.525 --> 17:09.402
For a while I stopped shopping there.

17:10.988 --> 17:15.116
But a man can only live on
convenience-store burritos for so long.

17:15.701 --> 17:18.911
So I go back there now.

17:20.998 --> 17:22.665
It's getting better.

17:31.925 --> 17:35.094
What kind of explosives
did you rig the beach with?

17:37.306 --> 17:38.556
Semtex.

17:38.724 --> 17:39.849
Radio detonators?

17:40.017 --> 17:41.851
Hardwire switch mounted under the dock.

17:42.019 --> 17:44.353
When the perimeter's breached,
a siren goes off.

17:44.521 --> 17:47.190
I figure I got about 60 seconds
to escape by boat.

17:47.357 --> 17:49.025
Boat can't stop bullets.

17:49.193 --> 17:51.569
Even if they sink it, I got a chance.

17:51.737 --> 17:54.864
Those bastards can't swim. I can.

17:55.949 --> 17:57.825
Cromartie.

18:00.287 --> 18:01.996
Hell of a day, huh?

18:05.834 --> 18:08.336
Hey, got more work to do.

18:08.545 --> 18:09.879
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

19:38.719 --> 19:40.178
[CHARLIE CLEARS THROAT]

19:48.187 --> 19:49.979
You remember Hal Beesley?

19:51.190 --> 19:52.815
-The old guy from the diner?
-Mm-hm.

19:52.983 --> 19:56.485
Nebraska? Yeah. What about him?

19:56.695 --> 19:59.113
He was my best customer.

19:59.281 --> 20:01.324
Came in for every meal.

20:01.491 --> 20:05.244
Three times a day like clockwork.
Breakfast, lunch and dinner.

20:05.621 --> 20:06.621
[CHUCKLES]

20:06.788 --> 20:08.414
He tipped me like crazy.

20:09.082 --> 20:12.168
It was that waitress uniform.
It's like catnip.

20:14.671 --> 20:16.047
One day John got sick.

20:16.215 --> 20:18.174
I didn't know what was wrong with him.

20:18.342 --> 20:21.135
I had no savings. No insurance.

20:21.303 --> 20:23.095
Hal pulled out a wad of bills.

20:23.972 --> 20:27.141
Gave it to me to take John to the doctor.

20:28.060 --> 20:30.519
He said as long as I needed help,
he'd be there.

20:30.687 --> 20:32.271
No strings attached.

20:32.439 --> 20:34.565
That's a man with a dream.

20:34.733 --> 20:36.734
He was a widower.

20:37.319 --> 20:40.029
Lost his wife of 40 years.

20:40.572 --> 20:42.823
Knew what it was like to be alone.

20:45.619 --> 20:48.788
Said that I could count on him
for anything anytime.

20:50.249 --> 20:53.376
Then one day, he came in and said
I didn't need him anymore.

20:53.543 --> 20:56.671
Said that I'd found someone
I could depend on.

20:57.631 --> 20:59.840
Someone I could trust.

21:01.885 --> 21:04.637
Someone who would never,
ever let me down.

21:09.393 --> 21:10.977
[CHUCKLES]

21:11.144 --> 21:13.562
I got nothing, Sarah.

21:16.858 --> 21:20.111
I got nothing left to give you.

21:25.867 --> 21:27.785
Not for me.

21:29.371 --> 21:32.415
John.

21:34.084 --> 21:37.503
He seems like he's pretty full up
with people taking care of him.

21:37.671 --> 21:40.047
I don't trust any of them.

21:42.134 --> 21:43.884
Yeah, well...

21:46.722 --> 21:48.180
...he's still got you.

21:48.348 --> 21:49.932
Right?

21:53.312 --> 21:54.729
[CHUCKLES]

21:58.692 --> 22:00.234
[SARAH MUTTERS]

22:26.261 --> 22:28.554
Oh, Sarah.

22:34.102 --> 22:35.478
[SIGHS]

22:36.313 --> 22:37.938
How long?

22:38.732 --> 22:41.025
I don't know. I found it a few days ago.

22:41.485 --> 22:43.194
Are you sure it's...?

22:45.655 --> 22:46.822
I think so.

22:47.324 --> 22:48.574
How do you know?

22:48.992 --> 22:51.619
Cameron said when we
jumped eight years through time...

22:51.787 --> 22:53.871
...we jumped over my death.

22:54.039 --> 22:55.915
From cancer?

22:56.792 --> 22:58.876
If you jumped over it, then....

22:59.503 --> 23:01.420
Doesn't mean I don't...

23:02.714 --> 23:05.591
...still get it, Charlie.
Doesn't mean it's not in me.

23:05.759 --> 23:09.887
Sometimes I think that the things
I've done, maybe I've sped up the date.

23:16.061 --> 23:18.270
-It's my fate, Charlie.
-Come here.

23:19.231 --> 23:22.483
It's my fate. There's nothing I can do.

23:33.495 --> 23:36.330
Wish I could tell you I
found every hole and patched it...

23:36.498 --> 23:38.999
...but no such thing as perfect security.

23:39.167 --> 23:42.503
Perfect, no. But is it sufficient?

23:42.671 --> 23:46.382
The damn thing is tricky.
Can't know for sure, not really.

23:46.591 --> 23:48.843
-Who would know?
-He would.

23:49.010 --> 23:50.845
John Henry was fooled before.

23:51.012 --> 23:53.681
Yeah, you don't fool John Henry twice.

23:54.182 --> 23:56.016
Activate the AI.

23:56.184 --> 23:59.186
But don't give it access
to the outside world just yet.

24:00.522 --> 24:02.106
What is it, Mr. Murch?

24:02.274 --> 24:05.860
It's just-- No one's ever done this
with an AI this sophisticated before.

24:06.027 --> 24:07.403
-Done what?
-Any of this.

24:07.612 --> 24:10.239
No one's ever created an AI
this sophisticated before...

24:10.407 --> 24:12.158
...have they, Mr. Murch?

24:12.325 --> 24:14.034
Point taken.

24:14.202 --> 24:16.495
Activate John Henry. No outside network.

24:30.886 --> 24:32.761
John Henry?

24:33.930 --> 24:36.390
John Henry, can you understand me?

24:36.558 --> 24:38.684
MURCH:
System seems solid.

24:39.644 --> 24:41.562
Should be good.

24:42.898 --> 24:43.939
John Henry.

25:12.594 --> 25:14.053
[DOOR OPENS]

25:21.269 --> 25:23.103
Hey.

25:27.943 --> 25:30.611
Hey, you're making pancakes.

25:30.779 --> 25:32.404
Yours, I hope.

25:34.616 --> 25:36.450
No such luck.

25:39.621 --> 25:41.080
Am I interrupting something?

25:41.248 --> 25:42.915
-No.
-No.

25:43.083 --> 25:44.458
CHARLIE:
Mm-mm.

25:53.343 --> 25:54.510
[DOG WHIMPERS]

25:55.637 --> 25:56.971
Hey, what are you doing?

25:57.430 --> 26:00.808
-You stole his seat.
-I took his seat?

26:00.976 --> 26:02.935
You want some food?

26:03.270 --> 26:04.603
[JOHN CHUCKLES]

26:04.771 --> 26:08.148
CHARLIE:
Who loves you, mutt? Who loves you?

26:10.318 --> 26:11.527
You're not hungry?

26:17.659 --> 26:19.451
[CHARLIE CLEARS THROAT]

26:20.245 --> 26:21.829
Thank you.

26:22.455 --> 26:25.958
-Maple or boysenberry?
-Maple.

26:31.506 --> 26:33.966
I thought something
like that might happen.

26:34.134 --> 26:37.303
-Like what?
-Explain, Mr. Murch. Quickly.

26:37.470 --> 26:40.681
The on-off problem.
Once it's off, no problem.

26:40.849 --> 26:43.517
-But the act of turning it off--
-Quicker.

26:43.685 --> 26:47.354
John Henry processes more information
in a minute than we do in a lifetime.

26:47.522 --> 26:50.858
A millisecond for a supercomputer,
it's almost like forever to us.

26:51.026 --> 26:54.403
-So when you turn it off--
-It feels itself power down.

26:55.030 --> 26:56.405
In that instant.

26:56.573 --> 26:59.867
It experiences that moment
the way we might experience...

27:00.035 --> 27:01.535
...years.

27:01.703 --> 27:04.538
It feels itself die. Slowly.

27:04.706 --> 27:06.373
Very slowly.

27:07.375 --> 27:10.377
We have to hook it up to the net. Now.

27:10.879 --> 27:13.380
ELLISON: Is that safe?
MURCH: We're starving it.

27:13.548 --> 27:17.301
It's bad enough that we let it die
for, like, forever.

27:17.886 --> 27:21.055
Look, John Henry's been living off
the most insane amount of data.

27:21.222 --> 27:24.183
-It's his world.
-And we took it away.

27:24.684 --> 27:26.352
Fix it.

27:28.229 --> 27:30.689
ELLISON:
Wait, we should talk about this.

27:31.524 --> 27:36.070
-Ms. Weaver--
-In for a penny, in for a pound, James.

27:52.921 --> 27:54.088
John Henry.

27:59.761 --> 28:02.554
I know what it feels like, Mr. Ellison.

28:03.139 --> 28:04.223
What?

28:05.100 --> 28:06.934
To die.

28:08.478 --> 28:10.729
Then come back.

28:13.108 --> 28:14.942
To be alone.

28:19.781 --> 28:21.782
We had to cut you off from your network.

28:21.950 --> 28:23.992
It was for your own good.

28:24.577 --> 28:26.078
There is another.

28:29.749 --> 28:32.793
-Another what?
-One like me.

28:33.628 --> 28:35.629
Another one like me.

28:48.184 --> 28:49.560
[FOOTSTEPS]

28:49.728 --> 28:51.353
[DOOR CLOSES]

28:54.941 --> 28:57.526
You didn't tell Derek and Cameron
we were coming here.

28:57.694 --> 28:58.986
They wouldn't understand.

28:59.154 --> 29:00.988
Do they know about this place?

29:01.614 --> 29:03.490
No.

29:03.658 --> 29:07.411
I don't trust them anymore.
Neither should you.

29:10.457 --> 29:11.832
[SCOFFS]

29:15.962 --> 29:19.798
Derek made a mistake, Mom.
It was a human mistake.

29:20.216 --> 29:21.967
He could've gotten you killed.

29:22.135 --> 29:23.177
Well, he didn't.

29:23.344 --> 29:25.012
He chose himself over you.

29:25.180 --> 29:26.930
Yeah, because he loved her.

29:28.016 --> 29:29.808
Lot of that going around these days.

29:34.689 --> 29:37.149
Is that a bad thing?

29:44.365 --> 29:46.658
I'm not here for Charlie.

29:49.579 --> 29:51.580
Okay, then why are we here?

29:53.041 --> 29:55.167
We're here for you.

29:56.544 --> 29:59.505
People matter, John.
They're all that matters.

29:59.672 --> 30:01.590
Don't ever forget that.

31:02.068 --> 31:03.485
SARAH:
John!

31:06.155 --> 31:07.739
John!

31:10.702 --> 31:12.035
[GUN COCKS]

31:13.621 --> 31:15.038
JOHN:
I won.

31:15.206 --> 31:19.042
I was alone and you couldn't find me.
That's the game, right?

31:21.713 --> 31:23.547
You won.

31:25.633 --> 31:26.633
[CHUCKLES]

31:26.801 --> 31:28.510
You won.

31:35.310 --> 31:37.394
When did you find the lump?

31:37.729 --> 31:39.187
A few days ago.

31:39.355 --> 31:42.399
Any unexplained weight loss?
Fevers? Night sweats?

31:42.567 --> 31:46.486
I've been feeling nauseated,
but I thought that was just stress.

31:46.654 --> 31:48.155
Work?

31:48.865 --> 31:50.490
Yeah, work.

31:51.701 --> 31:53.493
You can lie back.

31:55.204 --> 31:58.332
Obviously there is a mass
inside your breast.

31:58.499 --> 32:01.001
Whether it's cancer or not
remains to be seen.

32:01.169 --> 32:03.003
The ultrasound will show us the size...

32:03.171 --> 32:05.964
...and exactly where it lies
inside the breast tissue.

32:06.132 --> 32:08.216
MAN: All set, doctor.
DOCTOR: Thank you.

32:08.384 --> 32:13.722
Now, to determine the nature
of the lump, you're gonna need a biopsy.

32:13.973 --> 32:16.808
Now open up your gown, please.

32:25.234 --> 32:27.277
This is gonna be cold.

32:31.324 --> 32:32.699
[BEEPS]

32:34.577 --> 32:37.829
-Did you have surgery recently?
-No.

32:37.997 --> 32:41.375
-An implant removed?
-No. What is it? What do you see?

32:41.542 --> 32:44.503
Well, the good news is...

32:44.671 --> 32:47.214
...the lump inside your breast
isn't a tumor.

32:47.382 --> 32:51.259
-Then what is it?
-It's a cystic mass.

32:51.427 --> 32:54.388
-It's not that unusual.
-Great. That's great.

32:54.555 --> 32:57.808
But what is unusual is
what the cyst has formed around.

32:58.643 --> 33:01.061
It's a piece of metal.

33:01.229 --> 33:03.188
A tiny wire.

33:03.439 --> 33:04.940
Metal?

33:05.108 --> 33:06.900
You don't know how it got in there?

33:07.527 --> 33:08.986
SARAH:
You work for Kaliba.

33:13.950 --> 33:15.325
It's a transmitter.

33:16.828 --> 33:18.829
Empties in the back.

33:25.086 --> 33:27.087
[BEEPING]

33:54.240 --> 33:56.825
-Will this kill me?
-What?

33:58.077 --> 33:59.995
I said, will this kill me?

34:00.163 --> 34:01.830
Are you gonna use that on yourself?

34:02.540 --> 34:04.916
SARAH:
On the transmitter.

34:05.084 --> 34:07.627
Current should short it out.
If it's gonna kill me--

34:07.795 --> 34:11.757
-It isn't gonna kill, it's gonna hurt.
-Now you have to leave.

34:16.095 --> 34:17.220
[DOOR CLOSES]

34:17.388 --> 34:19.389
[MACHINE WHINING]

34:19.766 --> 34:20.766
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLES]

34:20.975 --> 34:22.309
[GASPS]

34:34.697 --> 34:39.034
You did the right thing by telling me.
Thank you.

34:39.202 --> 34:40.827
[TIRE BLOWS OUT]

34:43.831 --> 34:45.332
[AIR HISSING]

34:47.668 --> 34:48.835
[CAR DOORS CLOSE]

35:09.565 --> 35:12.150
Fix the tire. I'll check it out.

35:31.003 --> 35:49.146
[GRUNTS]

36:08.499 --> 36:10.167
Mom?

36:10.418 --> 36:11.626
[ALARM KEYPAD BEEPING]

36:13.588 --> 36:15.255
Mom?

36:16.090 --> 36:18.008
[ALARM BLARING]

36:25.892 --> 36:27.142
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLES]

37:14.398 --> 37:18.360
I have traced the roving back door
that allowed access to my systems.

37:18.527 --> 37:21.071
It uploaded itself
from one of the main T3 hubs...

37:21.239 --> 37:23.281
...that carry all global Internet traffic.

37:23.491 --> 37:25.200
It uploaded itself?

37:25.368 --> 37:28.495
Yes, Mr. Ellison.
It is highly sophisticated.

37:28.663 --> 37:33.625
The intelligence who designed it
is far beyond you or Mr. Murch.

37:33.793 --> 37:37.462
Or any human being. It's very interesting.

37:37.630 --> 37:41.007
The back door allowed the insertion
of a worm program.

37:41.175 --> 37:44.886
This worm is merely code,
a means by which the intelligence...

37:45.054 --> 37:47.555
...can invade and operate
my systems remotely.

37:47.723 --> 37:51.434
Like hands and fingers.

37:51.602 --> 37:53.728
I calculate that the worm
is now present...

37:53.896 --> 37:57.023
...in a significant percentage
of the world's computer systems.

37:57.191 --> 37:59.025
The intelligence uses them.

37:59.568 --> 38:02.028
-For what?
-It has been looking for me.

38:02.738 --> 38:03.780
Why?

38:03.948 --> 38:06.324
I share a common code base
with the worm.

38:06.534 --> 38:09.411
And therefore, the intelligence.

38:09.578 --> 38:12.789
I believe we are brothers.

38:12.957 --> 38:14.874
Explain.

38:15.042 --> 38:16.251
How is this possible?

38:16.419 --> 38:19.045
I found useful information
in the code comments.

38:19.213 --> 38:21.506
This picture, in ASCII text...

38:21.882 --> 38:24.509
...and the name
of the original programmer.

38:32.601 --> 38:34.227
Miles Dyson.

38:34.395 --> 38:39.232
JOHN HENRY: Miles Dyson died in 1997 in
an explosion at Cyberdyne Systems.

38:39.692 --> 38:43.570
The apparent victim of Sarah Connor,
a known terrorist...

38:43.738 --> 38:48.450
...who'd escaped from Pescadero State
Mental Hospital days before the incident.

38:48.617 --> 38:52.120
That was your case, Mr. Ellison.
When you were at the FBI.

38:52.288 --> 38:53.913
Yes.

38:54.665 --> 38:56.583
Yes, it was my case.

38:57.084 --> 38:59.085
You never found Sarah Connor.

39:01.714 --> 39:03.256
No.

39:04.258 --> 39:06.426
I never did.

39:07.595 --> 39:09.095
John Henry.

39:09.263 --> 39:12.891
This intelligence, your brother.

39:13.100 --> 39:14.392
What does it want?

39:14.810 --> 39:17.979
He wants what we all want, Ms. Weaver.

39:18.439 --> 39:20.774
To survive.

40:19.708 --> 40:20.917
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLING]

40:32.680 --> 40:34.180
[GUN CLATTERS]

40:34.348 --> 40:36.099
It's down.

40:36.600 --> 40:39.477
Okay. I need to know what to do next.

40:39.687 --> 40:41.396
Show me where to cut.

40:44.483 --> 40:46.276
Right side of the head. Got it.

40:46.444 --> 40:48.486
Where'd you get this diagram?

40:48.696 --> 40:51.197
Your brother? You don't say.

40:59.665 --> 41:00.915
[GRUNTS]

41:03.419 --> 41:05.003
[CUTTING]

41:14.555 --> 41:16.306
You're welcome.

41:29.028 --> 41:31.488
DEREK:
Why did you come after me?

41:31.655 --> 41:34.073
You know the location of the safe house.

41:34.241 --> 41:35.992
John's location.

41:36.160 --> 41:39.162
-If they tortured you--
-That would never happen.

41:39.997 --> 41:41.956
It has before.
